	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Non-tariff barriers found to hinder EAC trade</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The World Bank has recently published an Africa Trade Policy Note, ‘Addressing trade-restrictive, non-tariff measures on goods trade in the East African Community’. The study concludes that although the five members of the East African Community (EAC) have succeeded in eliminating many of the tariffs on intra-regional trade, ‘there has been more limited progress in addressing trade restrictive … non tariff barriers (NTBs)’. The EAC Customs Union Protocol makes specific reference (Article 13 (1)) to the need to eliminate NTBs and to refrain from imposing new ones. In particular it classified NTBs into four groups of which the first comprised those ‘with a low political and economic complexity and a low impact on EAC trade’ and were to be removed immediately in order to give some ‘quick wins’. They include trade obstacles such as non-recognition of EAC origin rules and certificates, import bans on milk, day-old chicks, beef, poultry, and multiple road blocks. </p><p>‘In practice’, the report finds ‘there have been very few “quick wins” over the past two years’ as it has proved to be very difficult to remove even this first tranche of NTBs. This is partly because of ‘the absence of a clearly defined monitoring mechanism with time limits for action’, so that each Partner State is responsible for voluntarily removing or reforming listed NTBs and is not subject to any sanctions if it fails to do so.</p><p>Such NTBs can prove to be a more severe barrier to trade than tariffs. Maize traders in the Arusha and Manyara regions, for example, have complained about the government ban on exporting their produce to neighbouring countries. Following a failure by the Tanzania Strategic Grain Reserves (SGR), Arusha branch, to purchase thousands of tonnes of their maize, the farmers claimed that they need to be able to sell to alternative buyers – but that these are across the border. It is reported that scores of lorries loaded with the grains have been stranded at SGR facility in Arusha after being told that the government agency was short of funds to purchase the crop.</p><p>A World Bank study on EAC health standards for dairy products points to the need to ensure that they actually protect the consumer in practice without being set at unattainably high levels as ‘vested interests ... try to manipulate standards and conformity assessment procedures in order to advance the sales of their own products and block market access for their competitors.’ The new EAC dairy standards which are largely based on the Codex Alimentarius may be problematic, it argues, ‘since the Codex assumes that consumer incomes and production infrastructure are equivalent to western levels.’ By focusing on processes that are common in developed countries (such as consuming mainly fresh pasteurised milk) but not necessarily in developing countries (where people mainly consume raw milk), the new standards sets requirements that most producers will not be able to meet.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank, ‘Addressing trade-restrictive, non-tariff measures on goods trade in the East African Community’, <i>Africa Trade Policy Notes</i>, August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Kirk_EN__01082010_WB_Addressing%20Trade%20Restrictive%20Non%20Tariff%20Measures%20on%20Goods%20Trade%20in%20the%20East%20African%20Community.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Kirk_EN__01082010_WB_Addressin...</a></p><p>Arusha Times, ‘Tanzania: Traders call for waiver of grain export ban’, 2 October 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201010040553.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201010040553.html</a></p><p>World Bank, ‘Non-tariff barriers and regional standards in the EAC dairy sector’, <i>Africa Trade Policy Notes</i>, Note no. 2, June 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRREGTOPTRADE/Resources/2_EAC_Dairy_Policy_Note_Final.pdf" target="_self">http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRREGTOPTRADE/Resources/2_EAC_Dai...</a></p><p>Overseas Development Institute/Commonwealth Secretariat, ‘Impediments to intra-regional trade in sub-Saharan Africa: The impact of non-tariff barriers on intra-regional trade in SADC’, <i>Hot Topic</i>, forthcoming</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>NTBs are often a more significant barrier to trade, and hence an obstacle to regional integration, than are tariffs. But they are more opaque – often involving subjective judgments over the balance to be struck between competing objectives (such as consumer protection and encouraging legitimate trade from which consumers will benefit). The example of the EAC, as one of the more fully developed ACP regional integration schemes, is important as a guide for the others. At a time when the Eastern and Southern African region is aiming to improve integration between the current regional trade agreements (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/content/view/full/859" target="_self">Eastern and Southern Africa free-trade area starts to take shape</a>’, October 2010), the scale of the challenge is underscored by the EAC’s failure to make ‘early wins’ on the NTB front even though its tariffs reduction has been relatively successful. Forthcoming research by the ODI on SADC NTBs shows that non-tariff barriers bear more heavily on intra-regional trade than they do on imports from outside the region. </p><p>Although some NTBs are opaque, others (such as export bans and road blocks) are very obvious. The possible reluctance of some governments to relinquish such controls, even when they have agreed to do so, emphasises one of the key requirements for a successful integration scheme: trust. Each member must trust the others to abide by agreed rules so that the removal of domestic controls does not create unacceptable risks.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
